2. For \(x \in (a, a + \delta)\), \(\phi(x) = 0\) and all its derivatives are also zero. Hence, \(\phi^{(k)}(a) = \lim_{x \to a^+} \phi^{(k)}(x) = 0\) for every \(k \geq 0\).
3. Similarly, \(\phi^{(k)}(b) = 0\) for every \(k \geq 0\).

Thus, every \(\phi \in \mathcal{C}^\infty_c(a,b)\) satisfies the derivative conditions, meaning that \(\mathcal{D}_{\{\infty\}}(a,b) = \mathcal{C}^\infty_c(a,b) = \mathcal{D}(a,b)\). 

Therefore, \(\mathcal{D}_{\{\infty\}}(a,b)\) is trivially dense in \(\mathcal{D}(a,b)\) (with any topology).

