1. Recognize that for any \(\phi \in \mathcal{C}^\infty_c(a,b)\), there exists a \(\delta > 0\) such that \(\phi\) is zero on \((-\infty, a + \delta] \cup [b - \delta, \infty)\).
2. Deduce that all derivatives of \(\phi\) are zero on \((a, a + \delta)\) and hence \(\phi^{(k)}(a) = 0\) for all \(k \geq 0\).
3. Similarly, deduce that \(\phi^{(k)}(b) = 0\) for all \(k \geq 0\).
4. Conclude that \(\mathcal{D}_{\{\infty\}}(a,b) = \mathcal{D}(a,b)\).
